We are prepping our data for various test we are going to perform. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tip2 <- tip %>% mutate( Preferance = as_factor(Preferance) ) glimpse(tip2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Rows: 60 Columns: 4 $ Name "Aanya", "Adit", "Aditi", "Akash", "Akshita", "Anandita", "… $ Gender "Female", "Male", "Female", "Male", "Female", "Female", "Fe… $ Preferance Veg, Veg, Veg, Non-veg, Non-veg, Non-veg, Non-veg, Veg, Veg… $ Tip 0, 0, 20, 0, 0, 0, 20, 35, 40, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 20, 0, … ``` ::: ::: ## ## What is our NULL Hypothesis for this data set? "**The average tip people give is higher for people who are non-vegetarians.**" **"Gender tends to affect the tipping."** To test our hypothesis, we will perform a series of steps. This will lead us to a conclusion regarding what we have stated. So, first we will find out the mean and standard deviation of tips across people with these 2 food preferences. ## Mean and Standard Deviation ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tip_mean1 <- mosaic::mean(~Tip, data = tip2) tip_sd1 <- mosaic::sd(~Tip, data = tip2) tip_mean1 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] 11.16667 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} tip_sd1 ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] 17.83556 ``` ::: ::: ## Histograms 1\. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tip2 %>% gf_histogram(~Tip, fill = ~Preferance) %>% gf_facet_wrap(vars(Preferance)) %>% gf_labs(title = "Do people tip?") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: According to the graph above, we see that there are more Vegetarians who don't tip compared to Non-vegetarians. 2\. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tip2 %>% gf_histogram(~Tip, fill = ~Gender) %>% gf_facet_wrap(vars(Gender)) %>% gf_labs(title = "Do people tip?") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-8-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: We facet by gender to get another perspective into looking at the data set. Does gender also affect how people tip? Looks like females tip slightly more than males! 3\. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tip2 %>% gf_histogram(~Tip, fill = ~Preferance, position = "dodge") %>% gf_labs(title = "Do people tip?") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: This graph helps us visualize the comparison between number of vegetarians and non-vegetarians who tip. Looks like, non-vegetarians tip more! But some vegetarians do tip Rs. 100! ### Check for Normality ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tip2 %>% crosstable(Tip~Preferance) %>% as_flextable ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}

The mean tip is slightly higher for vegetarians (12.3) compared to non-vegetarians (10.0), but with a higher standard deviation (21.9), suggesting more variability in the tipping behavior of vegetarians. -\>t-test: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} mosaic::t_test(Tip~Preferance, data = tip2, alternative = "greater") %>% broom::tidy() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 1 × 10 estimate estimate1 estimate2 statistic p.value parameter conf.low conf.high 1 2.33 12.3 10 0.503 0.308 46.9 -5.44 Inf # ℹ 2 more variables: method , alternative ``` ::: ::: This t-test tells us that Non-vegetarians tip 2.33 more than Vegetarians. the lower bound is −5.44 and the upper bound is Inf (infinity), reflecting a one-sided confidence interval due to the greater alternative hypothesis. The interval includes negative values, which means that there is no strong evidence that non-vegetarians tip more than vegetarians. Also, the p-value is greater than 0.05, so we cannot reject the null hypothesis. Difference in mean Tip between non-vegetarians and vegetarians is small and statistically insignificant. Since, there is such uncertainty in the t-tests we should perform some other tests. First, we shall check for normality using the shapiro test. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tip_mean_nonveg <- mean(~Tip, data = subset(tip2, Preferance == "Non-veg")) tip_mean_veg <- mean(~Tip, data = subset(tip2, Preferance == "Veg")) tip_diff <- tip_mean_nonveg - tip_mean_veg tip_diff ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] -2.333333 ``` ::: ::: -\>Shapiro test: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tip2 %>% filter(Preferance == "Non-veg") %>% select(Tip) -> NonVeg tip2 %>% filter(Preferance == "Veg") %>% select(Tip) -> Veg NonVeg ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 30 × 1 Tip 1 0 2 0 3 0 4 20 5 0 6 0 7 0 8 0 9 0 10 20 # ℹ 20 more rows ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} Veg ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 30 × 1 Tip 1 0 2 0 3 20 4 35 5 40 6 0 7 0 8 0 9 15 10 100 # ℹ 20 more rows ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} shapiro.test(NonVeg$Tip) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Shapiro-Wilk normality test data: NonVeg$Tip W = 0.71661, p-value = 2.747e-06 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} shapiro.test(Veg$Tip) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Shapiro-Wilk normality test data: Veg$Tip W = 0.6286, p-value = 1.661e-07 ``` ::: ::: These low p-values suggest that both distribution for non-veg and veg is not normal. Since, it is not normal, it is appropriate to conduct a Wilcox test for further analysis. -\>Wilcox Test: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} wilcox.test(Tip~Preferance, data = tip2, alternative = "greater", conf.int = TRUE, conf.level = 0.95) %>% broom::tidy() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning in wilcox.test.default(x = DATA[[1L]], y = DATA[[2L]], ...): cannot compute exact p-value with ties ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning in wilcox.test.default(x = DATA[[1L]], y = DATA[[2L]], ...): cannot compute exact confidence intervals with ties ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 1 × 7 estimate statistic p.value conf.low conf.high method alternative 1 -0.0000372 437 0.590 -0.00000420 Inf Wilcoxon rank … greater ``` ::: ::: The results suggest that there is no significant difference between non-veg and veg people who tip. The p-value also suggests that we don't have sufficient data to reject the null hypothesis. Now, we can do a Permutation test to analyse and help us come to a conclusion. -\>Permutation: A permutation test is a non-parametric test used to determine if there is any significant difference between 2 or more groups. We can use this when t-tests or the wilcox test does not work. - Preference ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} obs_diff_mean <- diffmean(Tip ~ Preferance, data = tip2) obs_diff_mean ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` diffmean -2.333333 ``` ::: ::: As per previous calculations of the diff mean, here also we see that the difference of means is -2.333333. So, this means that non-veg tips 2.3 less than veg. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} null_dist_tip1 <- do(4999) * diffmean(data = tip2, Tip ~ shuffle(Preferance)) null_dist_tip1 ``` ::: {.cell-output
